snippet.textDisplay:
As sad as this announcement makes me, I really have to express my respect for you guys. It's rare nowadays that artists get to end their stories when they want to. That's a hard and brave decision to make, but I think it will help DBZA stand the test of time. And that's something it definitely deserves.


I also wanted to share this little story: I was never what I would call fan of Dragonball Z. I saw it on and off as a kid on tv, but it only captured my attention by how different it was from other cartoons at the time. As a teenager, I remember seeing your early episodes and only thinking, "oh that's neat, I remember that, how wacky." Then, years later, I saw your rendition of the Frieza saga. And that was the first time I truly saw Dragonball for what it was, what it could be. I've watched that arc on your channel at least a dozen times since, and now I understand what this story, both yours and the original, means to so many people. Thank you for giving me and so many others this experience. DBZA is truly amazing.

snippet.textDisplay:
All good things must come to an end, and it takes great integrity to know when to let things go when its reached a satisfying conclusion.

I've followed you from episode 1, all the way from Goku asking if Picalo was a Yoshi, repeating "Mahogony" at random, and singing "Ghost Nappa" on random occasions.

In fact, I NEVER watched the original Dragon Ball Z, and watching your take I nevered NEEDED to. You captured its essense, while offering a more entertaining experience, with Krilin's owned counter, little Green, and a Vegeta rage soo big it caused my computer to go Blue Scree of death on me.

And to finalize with such a classic song, reminesent of how you did it "Your Waaaay", before ending with Goku's message that sometimes you have to move on and let the next generation take over, I am not sad. The only feeling I have for this is pride and admiration.

Your 11 years have inspired NUMEROUS people to do better. You have been a glowing example of artistic integrity. You have offered quality content by being deeply passionat to project that grew an empire. And it has been an absolute honor to share this decade of creativity as one of your audience members.

Maybe 5-10 years you may come back and take on where you left off (aging alongside Gohan and growing as he grew as well :D I mean.... DBZ took an equally solid break and return with their God saga :D ). Maybe you need time to rechagrge, gain perspective, and review what was done. Absence does make the heart grow fonder.

But even if you don't, this decade long love-letter to an amazing franchise that encouraged fans to want to know about this cultural phenomea will live on for years to come. It was a master piece of work, ad it will be replayed like many classical music. It will always be appreciated, and you crazy classy creators will never be forgotten.

So from this Space Duck living in non-Space Australia.... all I have left to say is....

You are hillarious, and I will quote everything you have ever said :)

P.S.: Quack.

Lani, you said that you guys aren't entitled to our time and viewership. I think for most people, that's the case, but not for me. You guys have brought me so much joy and entertainment over the years. You've helped me brighten people's days when I've shown them DBZA and Hellsing Ultimate Abridged. I remember watching the Hellsing Ultimate Abridged Finale livestream the day after my grandmother passed and being able to laugh and smile when I really needed that pick-me up. You are absolutely entitled to my time, viewership, and support. You are absolutely entitled to my loyalty.
Knowing that DBZA is over is sad. I was really looking forward to the Buu saga, but your creative freedom and peace of mind matters so much more. I haven't really gotten into your other projects, but I will (just as soon as I finish some college transfer stuff), and I really look forward to seeing everything you guys do.

You know what... For all that you did, thank you. For the work you put in, thank you. For the time, effort, and obvious metric fuck-tons of love that you put into writing, recording, dubbing, editing... I thank you all, Team Four Star. I'm happy for all that you've made with this. I'm happy for the experience that you've gained from it (as we all can see how it transitioned over to Hellsing Abridged) and I'm happy for experiencing the wit and characters that you reimagined for us all.

You've given me laughs that I have shared with my friends and family. I know we all would've loved to see what you could've done with the Buu saga, but at the same time, nobody wants to see a group of such loyal fans become disillusioned with such a large project to the point of disenfranchisement.

Thank you for all that you've given us. :)

snippet.textDisplay:
I think it's the sign of a true creative talent to recognize when it's time to put down the brush and call a work "done." Episode 60 was a perfect ending. A true love letter to not just to the Dragon Ball property, but to the Abridged series itself. It will stand as a shining example of a complete story that lasted exactly as long as it should. That, to me, triples its value.


I look forward to seeing what else Team Four Star brings us in the future.

snippet.textDisplay:
This is how Toriyama felt like when he was doing the buu arc, he was tired and he just wanted to end the series.

I’m sure you guys are the same, we are human beings and we have limits on how much we can do. I am a loyal fan that got the show introduced to me by my elder brother 6 years ago, and it feels hard to let it go. But I understand, I understand the effort that all of you has put in, just to entertain us. And I can’t even imagine myself and a many other people standing in your place and do the same.

I guess what I’m mainly trying to say here, is thank you. Thank you for dedicating 11 years for us. Thank you for making us laugh when we just had a bad day. Thank you for giving us a chance to revisit our beloved show. Thank you for everything. And guys, take it easy. Maybe one day, we will see you guys back in action.
